  "bib_entries": {
    "122661379": {
      "title": "Interaction of Markov processes",
      "abstract": "For a gentle approach to the problems connected with interacting Markov processes we review first what is known in the absence of interaction. For simplicity let S be a countable (or finite) set, and consider a countable (or finite if S is finite) collection of independent Markov processes on S,with common transition function P t (x,y), x, y ∈ S. It is natural to assume constant invariant measure, i.e., ::: ::: $$ \\sum\\limits_{{x \\in S}} {{{P}_{t}}(x,y)} = \\sum\\limits_{{y \\in S}} {{{P}_{t}}(x,y)} = 1, x,y S, t \\geqslant 0. $$ ::: ::: (0.1)"
    }
